In DPV measurements, the MWCNT-AuNP/GQD/PAMAM/tTG electrode in the absence of anti-tTG antibody shows a high decrease in peak current (Ip) in comparison to the anti-tTG incubated electrode due to immune-complex formation (Fig. 2
                           ) as in CV measurements. The inset plot between anti-tTG antibody concentrations and the relative Ip values with respect to the antigen tTG also shows hyperbolic curve (Fig. 2, inset [A]) following the linear equation [Ip (μA)=163.44 (μApg−1)×anti-tTG antibody (pg) + 18.46] and regression coefficient (R2) was 0.9717 (Fig. 2, inset [B]). The sensitivity of the sensor was 1297.94μA/cm2
                           pg−1and LOD for anti-tTG antibody in serum was calculated as 0.12 fg per 6μl (20fgml−1).

The specificity of the sensor with anti-tTG antibody and other non-specific serum proteins (CystatinC, Creatinine, Cardiac troponin I) was checked using DPV measurement. The DPV peak current (Ip) of the sensor after 10min incubation with 1pg per 6μl of non-specific serum proteins were found to be almost same or slightly reduced from the immobilized antigen (Fig. 4
                        ). The significant decrease in Ip value was obtained only in the case of anti-tTG antibody, which confirms the specificity of the sensor only to an anti-tTG antibody. The inset shows bar graph for relative peak current (Fig. 4[A]) and% relative peak current (Fig. 4[B]) with specific and non-specific serum proteins. The stability of the immobilized tTG electrode was studied by measuring the change in the DPV peak current every 30days of storage at 4°C. The sensor electrode was found stable for 6 months at 4°C only with 10% loss in the initial Ip of the immobilized tTG. The comparison of our method (GQD-PAMAM nanohybrid based celiac disease sensor) with earlier reported methods for the detection of antibodies raised in response to gluten ingestion in celiac susceptible individuals is summarized in Table 1
                        .
